                        <toDate standardDate="1837-06-13">13 June 1837</toDate>
                    </dateRange>
                    <citation>Wikipedia. "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ka%C3%BAxuma_N%C3%BApika" Accessed September 21, 2020. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ka%C3%BAxuma_N%C3%BApika
                        Brownlie, Robin Jarvis."Qánqon-Kámek-Klaúla" Encyclopedia.com. Last updated Jan 8, 2020. https://www.encyclopedia.com/social-sciences/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/qanqon-kamek-klaula</citation>
                    <descriptiveNote><p>Among Qánqon-Kámek-Klaúla's own people he was labelled títqattek, a culturally-specific gender identity for the Kutenai; Suzanne Crawford O'Brien, a modern scholar (https://doi.org/10.1080/13558358.2016.1215033) uses the term transgender to describe Qánqon-Kámek-Klaúla. To encompass these, Two-spirit people, defined in the Homosaurus [An LGBT+ Thesaurus which is a source for Georgian Paper gender terms] as "Self-identifying term used by indigenous people in North America to reconnect with the multiple gender and sexual roles in Native cultures" is included here.</p></descriptiveNote>
