            <biogHist> 
                <abstract>Kaúxuma Núpika ("Gone to the Spirits"), also known as Qánqon Kámek Klaúla ("Sitting in the Water Grizzly") or Manlike Woman, was a Kutenai person who lived in the early 19th century. Born in the 1780s, Qánqon-kámek-klaúla was raised and lived as a woman known as Qúqunok Pátke ("One Standing (Lodge) Pole Woman."). For a time she joined David Thompson and his expedition along the Columbia River and married one of Thompson's men. After a while she left her husband and returned to the Kutenai. Once returned, he claimed that his husband had transformed them from a women into a man. He adopted the name, Kaúxuma Núpika, and claimed to be a healer and prophet and lived as a man for the rest of his life. He took on his final name, Qánqon-Kámek-Klaúla, after crouching while crossing a stream (returning from an unsuccessful raid) so others would not "discern his sex".</abstract>
                <citation>Wikipedia. "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ka%C3%BAxuma_N%C3%BApika" Accessed September 21, 2020. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ka%C3%BAxuma_N%C3%BApika</citation>
